'''''Jesus freak''''' was originally a derogatory term applied to those involved in the [[Jesus movement]] of the [[1960s]] and [[1970s]] who were often considered overzealous in their passion for [[Jesus]]. It was used most often in relation to members of the ''[[Children of God]]'' movement. 

The term came into existence within the context of the so-called ''[[Freak scene]]'' of that era. Perhaps its most well-known usage was in the lyrics of [[Elton John]]'s song "[[Tiny Dancer]]" ("Jesus freaks, out in the street, handing out tickets to God," referring to [[Tract (literature)|gospel tracts]]), but it has also appeared in [[Felt (band)|Felt]]'s [[1986 in music|1986]] single "[[Ballad of the Band]]".  The term has recently been used frequently by [[Howard Stern]] and [[Ted Turner]]. 

However, many consider it a [[reclaim|reclaimed]] word, as it is also occasionally used today by [[Christians]], especially Christian youth, as a positive term to let others know that they are not ashamed of their belief in Jesus.  "Jesus Freak" also appeared as the title of the 1995 album by [[dc Talk]].

"Jesus Freaks" is also the name of a German youth movement that started in Hamburg in 1991.  to read about it (in German) http://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jesus_Freaks

